WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.478 --> 00:00:08.964
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:00:12.450 --> 00:00:16.434
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:16.687 --> 00:00:18.520
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: So
Shad, I thought maybe

00:00:18.520 --> 00:00:21.900
we could begin with how you
got started on the investing

00:00:21.900 --> 00:00:23.610
journey?

00:00:23.610 --> 00:00:25.320
FREDERICK "SHAD"
ROWE: Well, my father

00:00:25.320 --> 00:00:28.016
was in the advertising
business for most of his life,

00:00:28.016 --> 00:00:30.390
and he recommended to me that
I buy some Central Airlines

00:00:30.390 --> 00:00:33.390
with some money I made in the
summer on a construction job.

00:00:33.390 --> 00:00:35.600
So I bought 200 shares
of Central Airlines

00:00:35.600 --> 00:00:38.610
at $2.25 for $450.

00:00:38.610 --> 00:00:40.560
And I met the Chief
Executive Officer,

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:43.050
whose name was Lamar Muse.

00:00:43.050 --> 00:00:47.160
And they came over to my
parents' house one time

00:00:47.160 --> 00:00:47.860
and had dinner.

00:00:47.860 --> 00:00:50.070
And my mother's dog bit
his wife on the nose.

00:00:50.070 --> 00:00:52.080
[LAUGHTER]

00:00:52.080 --> 00:00:54.345
They didn't leave, but
it went to show you

00:00:54.345 --> 00:00:57.400
he was a good sport
and resilient.

00:00:57.400 --> 00:00:59.000
So that was something
kind of funny.

00:00:59.000 --> 00:01:00.430
But anyway, the stock went up.

00:01:00.430 --> 00:01:04.800
It was acquired about a year
and a half later by Frontier

00:01:04.800 --> 00:01:06.660
Airlines for $14 a share.

00:01:06.660 --> 00:01:11.146
So $2.25 turned into
$14 pretty quickly.

00:01:11.146 --> 00:01:12.895
And I just thought,
this beats sitting out

00:01:12.895 --> 00:01:16.460
in the sun carrying
forms around.

00:01:16.460 --> 00:01:17.680
And I was hooked for life.

00:01:17.680 --> 00:01:19.792
And that was a good
success to start with.

00:01:19.792 --> 00:01:21.250
I had a lot of
failures after that.

00:01:21.250 --> 00:01:23.090
But I kind of figured
it all out eventually.

00:01:23.090 --> 00:01:24.391
Maybe I have, I don't know.

00:01:24.391 --> 00:01:24.890
We'll see.

00:01:24.890 --> 00:01:26.134
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: Wow.

00:01:26.134 --> 00:01:28.002
So did you start
investing right away, or--

00:01:28.002 --> 00:01:29.960
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE:
Well, I bought a little.

00:01:29.960 --> 00:01:31.668
So I'd hear something,
and I'd buy stock,

00:01:31.668 --> 00:01:33.600
and just hearing
something about a stock

00:01:33.600 --> 00:01:35.584
isn't a very good
investment system,

00:01:35.584 --> 00:01:37.500
because you hear it from
people who don't know

00:01:37.500 --> 00:01:38.555
what they're talking about.

00:01:38.555 --> 00:01:40.929
It took a while to figure out
who did know what they were

00:01:40.929 --> 00:01:42.350
talking about and who didn't.

00:01:42.350 --> 00:01:46.260
But I'm always fascinated by
it and always interested in it.

00:01:46.260 --> 00:01:49.770
And you know, I kid
around about myself,

00:01:49.770 --> 00:01:52.805
but my wife took me to
this event every year

00:01:52.805 --> 00:01:54.515
called "Art About Town."

00:01:54.515 --> 00:01:56.400
And you would bid
on paintings, and I

00:01:56.400 --> 00:01:58.470
would bid on paintings
for less than I

00:01:58.470 --> 00:01:59.724
figured the frame value was.

00:01:59.724 --> 00:02:01.640
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: Less
than the frame value?

00:02:01.640 --> 00:02:02.710
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE:
Less than the frame value,

00:02:02.710 --> 00:02:04.001
because I was a value investor.

00:02:04.001 --> 00:02:07.230
And so people would say, well,
did you make money doing it?

00:02:07.230 --> 00:02:10.710
I said, no, I never
recognized a penny--

00:02:10.710 --> 00:02:12.240
they're all horrible.

00:02:12.240 --> 00:02:15.268
But at least, I had
some cheap frames.

00:02:15.268 --> 00:02:17.020
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: Wow.

00:02:17.020 --> 00:02:20.450
Shad, I think somewhere
in the mid '70s,

00:02:20.450 --> 00:02:23.574
you also started a banking or
a brokerage operation, right?

00:02:23.574 --> 00:02:25.990
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Well,
I worked for this firm called

00:02:25.990 --> 00:02:27.780
Schneider, Bernet &amp; Hickman.

00:02:27.780 --> 00:02:29.220
And I was a Syndicate Manager.

00:02:29.220 --> 00:02:30.547
I would bid the new issues.

00:02:30.547 --> 00:02:32.130
I would look at the
new issues and try

00:02:32.130 --> 00:02:34.320
to get the firm into the deals.

00:02:34.320 --> 00:02:36.850
And then I left
there, and you know,

00:02:36.850 --> 00:02:38.580
I wanted to start
my own firm, which

00:02:38.580 --> 00:02:43.530
I called Rowe and Company,
Investment Bankers/Brokers.

00:02:43.530 --> 00:02:45.030
We really were just
a brokerage firm

00:02:45.030 --> 00:02:48.280
and did a little investment
banking, but not much.

00:02:48.280 --> 00:02:50.920
And then I did that and
traded for the firm's account

00:02:50.920 --> 00:02:52.770
and made a little money.

00:02:52.770 --> 00:02:55.592
And then in 1985, I
decided to start a fund

00:02:55.592 --> 00:02:57.300
to share the joys of
short selling, which

00:02:57.300 --> 00:03:00.940
I was doing a lot of,
because the skyline in Dallas

00:03:00.940 --> 00:03:02.460
was just pure cranes--

00:03:02.460 --> 00:03:03.930
like it is here, now.

00:03:03.930 --> 00:03:06.060
But you know, there were
see-through buildings

00:03:06.060 --> 00:03:07.809
everywhere, and I
figured somebody bad was

00:03:07.809 --> 00:03:10.940
going to happen, so I
started short selling.

00:03:10.940 --> 00:03:12.690
PRANESH SRINIVASAN:
Were you short selling

00:03:12.690 --> 00:03:14.359
stocks or real estate?

00:03:14.359 --> 00:03:15.900
FREDERICK "SHAD"
ROWE: Well, stocks--

00:03:15.900 --> 00:03:19.402
bank stocks, real estate stocks,
real estate-related stocks.

00:03:19.402 --> 00:03:21.360
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: What
was the thesis, there?

00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:21.750
FREDERICK "SHAD"
ROWE: The thesis

00:03:21.750 --> 00:03:23.900
was it was terribly
overbuilt, and everyone

00:03:23.900 --> 00:03:27.180
was going go broke, which
I was absolutely right on.

00:03:27.180 --> 00:03:27.880
And they did.

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:32.100
And so I wouldn't
say that was fun,

00:03:32.100 --> 00:03:35.012
but it was good to be right.

00:03:35.012 --> 00:03:36.720
In fact, if I'd saved
my money and waited

00:03:36.720 --> 00:03:38.550
until things really
broke down, I

00:03:38.550 --> 00:03:39.930
could have made some great buys.

00:03:39.930 --> 00:03:43.970
And it just shows how every
dark cloud has a silver lining

00:03:43.970 --> 00:03:45.732
kind of deal.

00:03:45.732 --> 00:03:47.110
So I could've done--

00:03:47.110 --> 00:03:50.234
it's just a matter of which
side you're looking at it.

00:03:50.234 --> 00:03:51.900
PRANESH SRINIVASAN:
Do you think getting

00:03:51.900 --> 00:03:55.170
the timing right was important
with the short selling?

00:03:55.170 --> 00:03:57.150
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE:
Of course it was, sure.

00:03:57.150 --> 00:04:01.835
And you know, you know
what I found out was that--

00:04:01.835 --> 00:04:04.660
if you buy stock, and it goes
down, the most you can lose

00:04:04.660 --> 00:04:06.550
is the money that you put up.

00:04:06.550 --> 00:04:09.690
And as it goes down some more,
you have a smaller problem,

00:04:09.690 --> 00:04:11.200
and you don't worry about.

00:04:11.200 --> 00:04:13.390
But if you short a
stock, and it goes up--

00:04:13.390 --> 00:04:15.570
you're just sick, you
can't even breathe,

00:04:15.570 --> 00:04:17.694
because you can have
unlimited loss potential-- you

00:04:17.694 --> 00:04:22.770
could die and be incapacitated
and lose every dime you have.

00:04:22.770 --> 00:04:25.870
There's an overpriced stock
service I took for a while--

00:04:25.870 --> 00:04:29.890
late '80s-- and they
recommended shorting Microsoft.

00:04:29.890 --> 00:04:31.770
And every couple of
months, they'd say,

00:04:31.770 --> 00:04:33.720
hold for a better exit point.

00:04:33.720 --> 00:04:35.520
Well, hell, they
lost all their money.

00:04:38.070 --> 00:04:39.640
So it's not a good
solid business,

00:04:39.640 --> 00:04:43.250
and when I was doing it,
interest rates were high,

00:04:43.250 --> 00:04:46.495
real rates were high,
and broker's call

00:04:46.495 --> 00:04:48.479
was about where the prime was.

00:04:48.479 --> 00:04:50.770
So if you put up treasury
bills and then shorted stock,

00:04:50.770 --> 00:04:54.870
you'd get a broker's call
on the short position, which

00:04:54.870 --> 00:04:57.600
would mean that you'd be
up 15% when you started,

00:04:57.600 --> 00:04:58.655
and it was pretty good.

00:04:58.655 --> 00:05:00.630
And now, of course, you
have to pay to borrow them,

00:05:00.630 --> 00:05:02.190
so you're down when
you start, so there's

00:05:02.190 --> 00:05:02.910
a big difference, there.

00:05:02.910 --> 00:05:04.610
I didn't figure that
out until later,

00:05:04.610 --> 00:05:07.031
but that's why it
was attractive.

00:05:07.031 --> 00:05:09.030
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: Right,
and taxes also were--

00:05:09.030 --> 00:05:10.615
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Oh,
taxes were also the same.

00:05:10.615 --> 00:05:12.240
There were the same
taxes on dividends

00:05:12.240 --> 00:05:16.170
and interest and short sales,
and short-swing profits

00:05:16.170 --> 00:05:17.490
and long-term profits.

00:05:17.490 --> 00:05:19.680
Everything was taxed the
same, so it didn't matter.

00:05:19.680 --> 00:05:22.470
And so that was another
little added factor.

00:05:22.470 --> 00:05:24.580
Plus, you really
never had to cover.

00:05:24.580 --> 00:05:29.250
You could take the money
and pair the trades off,

00:05:29.250 --> 00:05:30.780
you know what I mean--

00:05:30.780 --> 00:05:32.280
cover it versus the
box, which would

00:05:32.280 --> 00:05:33.740
mean you could
buy it back-- hold

00:05:33.740 --> 00:05:36.544
a long position and short
position, all at $0.25 a share

00:05:36.544 --> 00:05:37.085
or something.

00:05:37.085 --> 00:05:38.460
You'd never have to
pay taxes for it.

00:05:38.460 --> 00:05:39.180
PRANESH SRINIVASAN:
Could you explain

00:05:39.180 --> 00:05:40.620
that a little bit, Shad, for us?

00:05:40.620 --> 00:05:41.786
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Sure.

00:05:44.160 --> 00:05:47.940
You know, if you're shorting
versus the box of stock,

00:05:47.940 --> 00:05:52.137
you would borrow the
shares that you had bought

00:05:52.137 --> 00:05:53.970
and deliver them against
your short position

00:05:53.970 --> 00:05:55.710
or hold them against
your short position.

00:05:55.710 --> 00:05:58.361
So you would have covered,
but not recovered.

00:05:58.361 --> 00:05:59.860
But everything would
be blocked out,

00:05:59.860 --> 00:06:02.366
and you could just
keep the tax money.

00:06:02.366 --> 00:06:05.850
And then that was outlawed
in the Tax Rule of 1985.

00:06:05.850 --> 00:06:08.785
But that made it a little
bit better business then.

00:06:08.785 --> 00:06:11.076
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: So you
were getting paid to borrow,

00:06:11.076 --> 00:06:13.190
the taxes were
favorable, and the market

00:06:13.190 --> 00:06:15.014
was not fairly valued
according to that.

00:06:15.014 --> 00:06:17.430
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: No, and
there was a lot more retail

00:06:17.430 --> 00:06:20.720
investing then than there
was the last few years.

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:23.100
So not as smart.

00:06:23.100 --> 00:06:26.400
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: So why
did you give up short selling?

00:06:26.400 --> 00:06:28.649
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Well,
it becomes all-consuming.

00:06:28.649 --> 00:06:30.990
You know, you'd think you'd
feel better about it as you

00:06:30.990 --> 00:06:33.690
get older, but it hurts worse.

00:06:33.690 --> 00:06:36.782
And my mother,
typically, would just

00:06:36.782 --> 00:06:38.490
always try to be
optimistic about things,

00:06:38.490 --> 00:06:39.537
and one time, she said--

00:06:39.537 --> 00:06:42.120
Shaddie, don't worry, I'm sure
something terrible will happen.

00:06:42.120 --> 00:06:43.844
[LAUGHTER]

00:06:43.844 --> 00:06:45.510
And that didn't make
me feel any better,

00:06:45.510 --> 00:06:48.360
but that was sort of the idea.

00:06:48.360 --> 00:06:50.920
You know, you were looking
for bad outcomes all the time,

00:06:50.920 --> 00:06:53.010
which, you know,
it's a happier life,

00:06:53.010 --> 00:06:55.292
if you're looking
for good outcomes.

00:06:55.292 --> 00:06:57.750
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: And so
after you gave up short selling,

00:06:57.750 --> 00:07:00.989
you moved on to finding small,
local companies in Texas.

00:07:00.989 --> 00:07:02.780
Can you talk to us a
little bit about that?

00:07:02.780 --> 00:07:04.363
FREDERICK "SHAD"
ROWE: Well, actually,

00:07:04.363 --> 00:07:06.680
in the time between
Central Airlines--

00:07:06.680 --> 00:07:09.240
I also owned small companies,
I owned Southwest Airlines

00:07:09.240 --> 00:07:11.700
when they had three and
then four airplanes--

00:07:11.700 --> 00:07:13.980
so I knew something about
the airline business,

00:07:13.980 --> 00:07:16.432
and I knew something
about advertising business

00:07:16.432 --> 00:07:17.890
a little bit,
because of my father.

00:07:17.890 --> 00:07:19.790
And so I was sort of set up--

00:07:19.790 --> 00:07:22.240
I owned some things
on those lines.

00:07:22.240 --> 00:07:27.610
And I find that one kind
of door leads to another,

00:07:27.610 --> 00:07:29.110
and everything is
kind of connected.

00:07:29.110 --> 00:07:30.870
We're all connected.

00:07:30.870 --> 00:07:33.230
And so, between my father--

00:07:33.230 --> 00:07:36.260
and you know, who I'm much
more friendly toward now

00:07:36.260 --> 00:07:38.290
than I was when he was
alive, unfortunately--

00:07:38.290 --> 00:07:43.440
but you could kind of get a
feel for different businesses.

00:07:43.440 --> 00:07:48.034
So in the end, the shorts would
eventually turned into longs.

00:07:48.034 --> 00:07:49.700
I bought back-- I
owned-- it was short--

00:07:49.700 --> 00:07:53.610
WPP Group in 1991, and
then covered in '92

00:07:53.610 --> 00:07:56.180
and covered in '91 and
then ended up buying it

00:07:56.180 --> 00:07:58.090
and made a lot on it.

00:07:58.090 --> 00:08:00.392
And Southwest Airlines,
I did very well on.

00:08:00.392 --> 00:08:01.850
PRANESH SRINIVASAN:
So when did you

00:08:01.850 --> 00:08:03.944
buy your first shares
of Southwest Airlines?

00:08:03.944 --> 00:08:05.360
FREDERICK "SHAD"
ROWE: About 1974.

00:08:05.360 --> 00:08:06.500
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: 1974?

00:08:06.500 --> 00:08:07.360
FREDERICK "SHAD"
ROWE: That's about--

00:08:07.360 --> 00:08:08.520
I still have some.

00:08:08.520 --> 00:08:09.880
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: You
still have the same shares--

00:08:09.880 --> 00:08:12.005
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: No,
no, not the same shares.

00:08:12.005 --> 00:08:14.702
I sold most of it, but the
stuff is very valuable.

00:08:14.702 --> 00:08:15.998
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: Wow.

00:08:15.998 --> 00:08:20.015
Would you know how much the
revenues have compounded by

00:08:20.015 --> 00:08:21.390
or the stock price
has compounded

00:08:21.390 --> 00:08:22.160
by since you bought it?

00:08:22.160 --> 00:08:24.118
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE:
Oh, it was probably 27%.

00:08:24.118 --> 00:08:24.830
It was huge.

00:08:24.830 --> 00:08:26.480
PRANESH SRINIVASAN:
20% over 30+ years.

00:08:26.480 --> 00:08:26.740
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Yes.

00:08:26.740 --> 00:08:27.860
It's amazing what it did.

00:08:27.860 --> 00:08:29.090
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: What
was it about how Southwest

00:08:29.090 --> 00:08:30.230
that got your attention?

00:08:30.230 --> 00:08:30.890
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE:
Well, Lamar Muse.

00:08:30.890 --> 00:08:32.820
He's the same guy that was
the head of Central Airlines.

00:08:32.820 --> 00:08:33.205
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: Right.

00:08:33.205 --> 00:08:35.720
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: And
so I felt like I knew him.

00:08:35.720 --> 00:08:38.531
And it was obvious to me that
they were doing something

00:08:38.531 --> 00:08:39.530
better, faster, cheaper.

00:08:39.530 --> 00:08:41.988
They were flying between Dallas
and San Antonio and Houston

00:08:41.988 --> 00:08:44.570
on a tight schedule and
doing it for not much

00:08:44.570 --> 00:08:46.470
than the price of a bus ticket.

00:08:46.470 --> 00:08:47.900
So the traffic was expanding.

00:08:47.900 --> 00:08:50.109
They were stimulating the
market, and it was growing.

00:08:50.109 --> 00:08:51.691
And they did that
everywhere they went

00:08:51.691 --> 00:08:52.880
all over the United States.

00:08:52.880 --> 00:08:54.460
And now, they've gone abroad.

00:08:54.460 --> 00:08:56.409
And you know, it's
a better story.

00:08:56.409 --> 00:08:57.950
They have one airplane
that they fly.

00:08:57.950 --> 00:09:00.117
They just threw an
engine out, I saw.

00:09:00.117 --> 00:09:01.200
It was on the news, today.

00:09:01.200 --> 00:09:07.499
But it was just a once in
a lifetime kind of deal.

00:09:07.499 --> 00:09:09.290
And to do it in an
airline is very unusual,

00:09:09.290 --> 00:09:14.075
because really it never has
shown loss in all these years.

00:09:14.075 --> 00:09:16.481
And other ones went
broke all the time.

00:09:16.481 --> 00:09:18.230
But they didn't put
their customers first.

00:09:18.230 --> 00:09:20.676
They put themselves first.

00:09:20.676 --> 00:09:22.550
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: And
their employees, too.

00:09:22.550 --> 00:09:23.150
They treat--

00:09:23.150 --> 00:09:23.780
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Yeah,
they treat everybody well.

00:09:23.780 --> 00:09:25.370
PRANESH SRINIVASAN:
--very well, yeah.

00:09:25.370 --> 00:09:29.570
So around 15 years ago, maybe,
or a little older than that,

00:09:29.570 --> 00:09:31.040
you changed your outlook again--

00:09:31.040 --> 00:09:33.590
focusing on companies
that can scale--

00:09:33.590 --> 00:09:36.024
do things faster, better,
cheaper for the customers.

00:09:36.024 --> 00:09:37.190
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Yeah.

00:09:37.190 --> 00:09:39.606
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: How did
this change happen, and maybe,

00:09:39.606 --> 00:09:41.340
give us some examples?

00:09:41.340 --> 00:09:45.710
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Well,
it was part of an odd man

00:09:45.710 --> 00:09:46.460
out kind of thing.

00:09:46.460 --> 00:09:49.550
You know, if you own
stock in a company,

00:09:49.550 --> 00:09:53.360
you're kind of second rate
compared to the management.

00:09:53.360 --> 00:09:55.620
You know, they don't
always tell you the truth,

00:09:55.620 --> 00:09:57.000
and they're manipulating you.

00:09:57.000 --> 00:09:59.250
But if you think the company
is really doing something

00:09:59.250 --> 00:10:03.080
for the stakeholders, for the
shareholders, for the customers

00:10:03.080 --> 00:10:05.510
than for themselves, you
feel a lot better about it.

00:10:05.510 --> 00:10:07.670
So I feel better as an
investor if I've invested

00:10:07.670 --> 00:10:09.840
in a company like that.

00:10:09.840 --> 00:10:11.990
So better, faster,
cheaper, and for-- and

00:10:11.990 --> 00:10:16.500
not to-- the customer, and to
the delight of the customer.

00:10:16.500 --> 00:10:18.799
And be on a scale
that if it works in--

00:10:18.799 --> 00:10:20.340
oh, and another
thing in advertising,

00:10:20.340 --> 00:10:22.214
I did-- this WPP Group
I talked to you about,

00:10:22.214 --> 00:10:25.470
where Martin Sorrell
just left, he got fired.

00:10:25.470 --> 00:10:29.120
But he said that the
word globalization

00:10:29.120 --> 00:10:31.601
is a misnomer, that the better
word is Americanization.

00:10:31.601 --> 00:10:34.100
People all over the world really
want to live the way we do,

00:10:34.100 --> 00:10:34.810
here.

00:10:34.810 --> 00:10:36.393
I don't know whether
you believe that.

00:10:36.393 --> 00:10:38.185
I think there's something to it.

00:10:38.185 --> 00:10:38.660
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: Yeah.

00:10:38.660 --> 00:10:40.760
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: So
if it's a success here,

00:10:40.760 --> 00:10:42.610
it can be a success elsewhere.

00:10:42.610 --> 00:10:44.810
And that's certainly
been the case of airlines

00:10:44.810 --> 00:10:49.490
and of Starbucks,
Amazon-- you know,

00:10:49.490 --> 00:10:51.680
all these companies operate
throughout the world.

00:10:51.680 --> 00:10:55.470
And you know, you used to talk
about the law of large numbers.

00:10:55.470 --> 00:10:57.140
Well, hell, you need
to own a stock that

00:10:57.140 --> 00:10:57.980
has a large number,
because there

00:10:57.980 --> 00:10:59.688
are a large number of
people in the world

00:10:59.688 --> 00:11:03.110
and a large number of
square miles to cover,

00:11:03.110 --> 00:11:05.860
and you've got to get out there
before someone beats you to it.

00:11:05.860 --> 00:11:08.290
I think these big companies
have a huge advantage, now.

00:11:08.290 --> 00:11:13.820
Rather than big, cumbersome
oafs, like they used to be,

00:11:13.820 --> 00:11:16.160
they're really big and
strong and powerful,

00:11:16.160 --> 00:11:18.227
and they just win-win-win.

00:11:18.227 --> 00:11:20.310
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: So
following up on that, Shad,

00:11:20.310 --> 00:11:23.180
recently I think you
wrote about the necessity

00:11:23.180 --> 00:11:25.250
of large numbers--

00:11:25.250 --> 00:11:27.590
that large numbers are not
just needed to compete,

00:11:27.590 --> 00:11:29.112
but to actually succeed.

00:11:29.112 --> 00:11:30.320
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Right.

00:11:30.320 --> 00:11:31.131
PRANESH SRINIVASAN:
So can you talk to us

00:11:31.131 --> 00:11:32.130
a little bit about that?

00:11:32.130 --> 00:11:34.130
Why do you think large
numbers are a necessity?

00:11:34.130 --> 00:11:37.520
And maybe give us an example
of a company that you think

00:11:37.520 --> 00:11:38.807
has efficiency going for it?

00:11:38.807 --> 00:11:41.223
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: We can't
talk about Google, can we?

00:11:41.223 --> 00:11:41.586
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: Uh.

00:11:41.586 --> 00:11:43.044
FREDERICK "SHAD"
ROWE: I'm teasing.

00:11:44.790 --> 00:11:45.980
Well, all of them, really.

00:11:45.980 --> 00:11:48.400
You know, Southwest Airlines
now is going to Mexico.

00:11:48.400 --> 00:11:49.940
They're going in the Caribbean.

00:11:49.940 --> 00:11:53.150
They're big enough
to do it, and no one

00:11:53.150 --> 00:11:55.430
would sit aside
and let Southwest

00:11:55.430 --> 00:11:56.664
do to them what they did.

00:11:56.664 --> 00:11:58.705
I mean, Southwest, I think
couldn't happen again,

00:11:58.705 --> 00:12:00.890
because people are just smarter.

00:12:00.890 --> 00:12:04.710
I think that board
compositions have changed.

00:12:04.710 --> 00:12:06.660
I think the people
are more attentive.

00:12:06.660 --> 00:12:10.400
And you know, the kind of
dull, kind of half senile Chief

00:12:10.400 --> 00:12:13.215
Executive Officer who sits
there and acts like a dictator--

00:12:13.215 --> 00:12:13.840
they're over.

00:12:13.840 --> 00:12:16.040
And women on the boards
have helped, I think.

00:12:16.040 --> 00:12:19.015
And there is just
more visibility,

00:12:19.015 --> 00:12:22.904
and it's hard to be as
secretive as people used to be.

00:12:22.904 --> 00:12:24.320
I think that
governance is better,

00:12:24.320 --> 00:12:27.050
and I think the opportunities
are better perceived.

00:12:27.050 --> 00:12:30.440
And investors
aren't any smarter,

00:12:30.440 --> 00:12:34.239
but I think the whole investment
situation has improved.

00:12:34.239 --> 00:12:36.280
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: And
I think you also stressed

00:12:36.280 --> 00:12:38.110
on efficiency, right, Shad?

00:12:38.110 --> 00:12:41.739
And you say that Costco is not
just efficient, but elegant.

00:12:41.739 --> 00:12:43.530
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE:
Oh yeah, it's great.

00:12:43.530 --> 00:12:46.730
It's fun to be there,
fun to shop there.

00:12:46.730 --> 00:12:48.290
You save money.

00:12:48.290 --> 00:12:50.405
You get great products,
you get great value.

00:12:50.405 --> 00:12:52.880
You see the same people there.

00:12:52.880 --> 00:12:55.647
And I think the shopping
is sort of an adventure.

00:12:55.647 --> 00:12:56.355
It's kind of fun.

00:12:56.355 --> 00:12:59.270
And they put things in the
store just to get you back.

00:12:59.270 --> 00:13:01.228
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: How
did you approach Costco

00:13:01.228 --> 00:13:02.870
as an investment decision?

00:13:02.870 --> 00:13:04.029
Did you--

00:13:04.029 --> 00:13:06.070
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE:
Well, I liked going there.

00:13:06.070 --> 00:13:06.640
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: OK.

00:13:06.640 --> 00:13:08.345
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: It's
probably as simple as that.

00:13:08.345 --> 00:13:10.636
I thought, if I like it,
other people probably like it,

00:13:10.636 --> 00:13:12.722
and they do.

00:13:12.722 --> 00:13:15.360
You want to save money,
you want to get value--

00:13:15.360 --> 00:13:16.860
you don't care about
the brand name.

00:13:16.860 --> 00:13:25.096
I mean, the brand-- what
is it, Kingwood, is it?

00:13:25.096 --> 00:13:26.695
It's great stuff.

00:13:26.695 --> 00:13:28.070
PRANESH SRINIVASAN:
The Kirkland?

00:13:28.070 --> 00:13:30.670
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Kirkland.

00:13:30.670 --> 00:13:32.680
Well, I'm losing my
mind, here, but yeah.

00:13:32.680 --> 00:13:33.560
It's really good.

00:13:33.560 --> 00:13:35.780
I like everything about it.

00:13:35.780 --> 00:13:37.720
One time, I was at
this investment group,

00:13:37.720 --> 00:13:41.754
and the deal on the
dinner we were going to

00:13:41.754 --> 00:13:43.920
was that the person who had
the worst bottle of wine

00:13:43.920 --> 00:13:45.610
had to buy dinner.

00:13:45.610 --> 00:13:47.660
And so I went, and I
took a bottle of wine

00:13:47.660 --> 00:13:50.236
that my wife had picked out
from Constellation Brands.

00:13:50.236 --> 00:13:51.860
I can't remember the
name of it, but it

00:13:51.860 --> 00:13:57.280
was a 92 on the wine or
whatever board, or something.

00:13:57.280 --> 00:14:00.290
But anyway, I heard the
waitress complaining and saying,

00:14:00.290 --> 00:14:04.130
this wine is flawed,
the cork is no good.

00:14:04.130 --> 00:14:07.095
And then they didn't put
wrap it up in tin foil,

00:14:07.095 --> 00:14:07.970
so I know what it is.

00:14:07.970 --> 00:14:11.195
I said, all right, I give
up-- it's me, I'll buy dinner.

00:14:11.195 --> 00:14:16.250
And I wrote a letter
to Jim Sinegal,

00:14:16.250 --> 00:14:19.300
saying that I'd had this
horrible experience.

00:14:19.300 --> 00:14:21.930
And by golly,
Constellation Brands

00:14:21.930 --> 00:14:25.910
sent me a gift
certificate for Costco

00:14:25.910 --> 00:14:28.616
to give me my money back.

00:14:28.616 --> 00:14:30.990
You know, I just made
a huge profit on it

00:14:30.990 --> 00:14:33.291
and bought more stock.

00:14:33.291 --> 00:14:35.540
And then I did the same thing
to McDonald's and talked

00:14:35.540 --> 00:14:36.500
about something terrible
that happened there.

00:14:36.500 --> 00:14:38.090
And I got a form letter back--

00:14:38.090 --> 00:14:42.450
sorry for your bad
experience and just nothing.

00:14:42.450 --> 00:14:45.090
But you know, that's sort
of a heroic response--

00:14:45.090 --> 00:14:47.750
just going overboard,
bending over backwards

00:14:47.750 --> 00:14:49.930
to make people happy.

00:14:49.930 --> 00:14:52.900
And if the customer comes
first, you get ahead.

00:14:52.900 --> 00:14:56.134
And if it doesn't,
you get behind.

00:14:56.134 --> 00:14:58.050
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: So
I think when you said--

00:14:58.050 --> 00:14:59.466
customer comes
first, I'm reminded

00:14:59.466 --> 00:15:01.850
of another one of your
nice characterizations

00:15:01.850 --> 00:15:04.500
about stage one companies,
stage two companies,

00:15:04.500 --> 00:15:06.000
and stage three companies.

00:15:06.000 --> 00:15:08.019
And these aren't to do
with size of the company

00:15:08.019 --> 00:15:08.935
or age of the company.

00:15:08.935 --> 00:15:10.455
They're with how the company--

00:15:10.455 --> 00:15:11.960
FREDERICK "SHAD"
ROWE: How they act.

00:15:11.960 --> 00:15:14.293
In stage one-- everything's
new-- you're doing something

00:15:14.293 --> 00:15:16.250
better, faster, cheaper
for the customer.

00:15:16.250 --> 00:15:17.630
Your stock is soaring.

00:15:17.630 --> 00:15:20.088
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: Can you
give us examples of each stage?

00:15:20.088 --> 00:15:23.467
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Well, any
little company that takes off.

00:15:23.467 --> 00:15:26.050
Southwest Airlines has been kind
of stage one the whole career

00:15:26.050 --> 00:15:28.186
it's had.

00:15:28.186 --> 00:15:30.950
And stage two is maybe
like a Starbucks,

00:15:30.950 --> 00:15:34.600
where they start selling
tea and different food

00:15:34.600 --> 00:15:39.500
and trying to get more
money from the same person.

00:15:39.500 --> 00:15:43.730
And stage three is most airlines
and banks and everything else,

00:15:43.730 --> 00:15:46.135
where there's no question
they're out to get you.

00:15:46.135 --> 00:15:47.510
PRANESH SRINIVASAN:
So how do you

00:15:47.510 --> 00:15:51.335
detect this change between
stage two and stage three, Shad?

00:15:51.335 --> 00:15:53.960
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Well, I'm
a customer, just like you are.

00:15:53.960 --> 00:15:54.918
It's obvious, isn't it?

00:15:58.140 --> 00:15:59.204
That's what I think.

00:15:59.204 --> 00:16:01.370
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: So what
are the hallmarks, Shad,

00:16:01.370 --> 00:16:03.695
of a great business?

00:16:03.695 --> 00:16:05.820
Like, these stage two,
stage one kind of business--

00:16:05.820 --> 00:16:06.390
what are the hallmarks?

00:16:06.390 --> 00:16:07.280
FREDERICK "SHAD"
ROWE: Well, I would

00:16:07.280 --> 00:16:09.240
love to find a business that was
doing something better, faster,

00:16:09.240 --> 00:16:11.900
cheaper on a scale that
could be taken globally,

00:16:11.900 --> 00:16:13.940
that I'd seen it work in
the United States, that

00:16:13.940 --> 00:16:15.230
had great management.

00:16:15.230 --> 00:16:17.021
You know, I don't know
how you define that,

00:16:17.021 --> 00:16:18.380
but you know it when you see it.

00:16:18.380 --> 00:16:24.410
And some valuation that somehow
you could think was reasonable.

00:16:24.410 --> 00:16:27.210
And that sounded like that--

00:16:27.210 --> 00:16:29.900
I was laughing the other day
about that David Allan Coe

00:16:29.900 --> 00:16:31.050
song.

00:16:31.050 --> 00:16:32.992
You know, what was it--

00:16:32.992 --> 00:16:35.450
I think your song is perfect,
but you haven't said anything

00:16:35.450 --> 00:16:40.680
about mama or trains or being
drunk or falling off the bus--

00:16:40.680 --> 00:16:43.370
but all the
ingredients are there,

00:16:43.370 --> 00:16:46.070
just like the ingredients are
there for a perfect stock.

00:16:46.070 --> 00:16:48.440
And you're always looking
for the perfect stock.

00:16:48.440 --> 00:16:48.950
PRANESH SRINIVASAN:
Do you do you

00:16:48.950 --> 00:16:50.930
focus on capital
intensivity at all, when

00:16:50.930 --> 00:16:52.360
you look at a great company?

00:16:52.360 --> 00:16:54.140
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Capital
intensiv-- capital what?

00:16:54.140 --> 00:16:55.730
PRANESH SRINIVASAN:
Capital intensiveness--

00:16:55.730 --> 00:16:57.240
how they use their
balance sheet.

00:16:57.240 --> 00:16:58.680
Are those things you look at?

00:16:58.680 --> 00:16:59.490
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE:
Well, I look at it.

00:16:59.490 --> 00:17:01.172
But I presume they
know more than I do,

00:17:01.172 --> 00:17:02.630
so I'm not too
judgmental about it.

00:17:02.630 --> 00:17:03.660
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: OK.

00:17:03.660 --> 00:17:05.076
So let's invert
that a little bit.

00:17:05.076 --> 00:17:07.550
You know, like Carl
Jacobi and Charlie Munger.

00:17:07.550 --> 00:17:09.932
So what are some things you
want to avoid in a business?

00:17:09.932 --> 00:17:12.140
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Well,
If you were still short,

00:17:12.140 --> 00:17:13.250
I'd want the same thing.

00:17:13.250 --> 00:17:15.454
You know, if it's not doing
better, faster, cheaper,

00:17:15.454 --> 00:17:16.579
it's doing something worse.

00:17:16.579 --> 00:17:18.470
It irritates people.

00:17:18.470 --> 00:17:21.160
They don't like it, and
business is going down.

00:17:21.160 --> 00:17:24.099
And it has no
potential overseas,

00:17:24.099 --> 00:17:27.420
because it has no potential
in the United States.

00:17:27.420 --> 00:17:29.746
You'd invert it, and it
would be perfect inversion.

00:17:29.746 --> 00:17:31.870
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: Are
there industries or sectors

00:17:31.870 --> 00:17:33.920
that you would avoid?

00:17:33.920 --> 00:17:34.780
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Well,
I don't think that way.

00:17:34.780 --> 00:17:36.821
I think of the ones that
I would be attracted to.

00:17:36.821 --> 00:17:38.680
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: OK.

