00:20:07.030 --> 00:20:09.280
That's a good reason to do it.

00:20:09.280 --> 00:20:11.200
You get a better
bargain that way.

00:20:11.200 --> 00:20:13.240
But I think in the
long term, it doesn't

00:20:13.240 --> 00:20:14.990
make that much difference
when you buy it,

00:20:14.990 --> 00:20:17.110
if you buy the right company.

00:20:17.110 --> 00:20:20.170
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: So let's
focus on that a little bit--

00:20:20.170 --> 00:20:22.000
the valuation, right.

00:20:22.000 --> 00:20:23.710
How do you approach
valuation when

00:20:23.710 --> 00:20:25.540
deciding to buy a business?

00:20:25.540 --> 00:20:27.950
What is an upper bound
you're willing to pay?

00:20:27.950 --> 00:20:29.519
How do you arrive at that?

00:20:29.519 --> 00:20:31.060
FREDERICK "SHAD"
ROWE: Well, I'd just

00:20:31.060 --> 00:20:33.760
want to see how you can pay
10 times what you thought it

00:20:33.760 --> 00:20:35.040
was eventually going to earn.

00:20:35.040 --> 00:20:39.880
That would be OK with me, if
you had a pretty high degree

00:20:39.880 --> 00:20:41.110
of confidence in it.

00:20:41.110 --> 00:20:43.174
Because with interest
rates where they are,

00:20:43.174 --> 00:20:45.340
you've got to think what
you can do with your money.

00:20:45.340 --> 00:20:47.620
And if people say,
well, the market

00:20:47.620 --> 00:20:49.640
is very overpriced,
and the NASDAQ

00:20:49.640 --> 00:20:52.510
sells at 33 times earnings
or whatever it sells at--

00:20:52.510 --> 00:20:55.740
well, you know, what's the
yield on a 10-year government?

00:20:55.740 --> 00:20:58.385
3%-- that's 33 times earnings.

00:20:58.385 --> 00:21:00.397
And that's the most
they're going to earn.

00:21:00.397 --> 00:21:02.480
So the companies have a
chance to earn a lot more.

00:21:02.480 --> 00:21:06.080
So I think stocks are
probably cheap relative

00:21:06.080 --> 00:21:08.567
to your choices of what
you can do with the money.

00:21:08.567 --> 00:21:09.775
Real estate isn't any better.

00:21:12.580 --> 00:21:14.970
Farming-- well, I don't know
what you're going to do.

00:21:14.970 --> 00:21:16.650
But your choices are limited.

00:21:16.650 --> 00:21:20.320
You know, stock is people,
it's real estate, it's capital,

00:21:20.320 --> 00:21:21.880
it's machines.

00:21:21.880 --> 00:21:24.460
It's being put together
by smart people,

00:21:24.460 --> 00:21:28.000
working and creating
value and growing--

00:21:28.000 --> 00:21:28.670
pretty exciting.

00:21:28.670 --> 00:21:32.310
And it doesn't excite people
very much, now, but it will.

00:21:32.310 --> 00:21:34.070
They haven't thought it through.

00:21:34.070 --> 00:21:36.880
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: So once
you buy a stock, ideally, Shad,

00:21:36.880 --> 00:21:38.110
you never want to sell it.

00:21:38.110 --> 00:21:42.800
You write fairly well that
selling creates two problems,

00:21:42.800 --> 00:21:43.760
right?

00:21:43.760 --> 00:21:45.250
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Right.

00:21:45.250 --> 00:21:46.780
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: The tax
problem, and the problem when--

00:21:46.780 --> 00:21:47.440
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE:
Then you pay taxes,

00:21:47.440 --> 00:21:49.620
and you've got to
replace the investment.

00:21:49.620 --> 00:21:51.649
You've got to be right twice.

00:21:51.649 --> 00:21:53.440
All you've got to do
on a real growth cycle

00:21:53.440 --> 00:21:55.859
is to be right once.

00:21:55.859 --> 00:21:57.400
PRANESH SRINIVASAN:
But sometimes you

00:21:57.400 --> 00:21:58.490
still have to sell, Shad.

00:21:58.490 --> 00:21:59.040
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Sure.

00:21:59.040 --> 00:22:01.414
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: And do
you sell because the situation

00:22:01.414 --> 00:22:04.280
changes, or do you sell also
sometimes because the price

00:22:04.280 --> 00:22:05.862
runs up too much?

00:22:05.862 --> 00:22:06.820
How do you think of it?

00:22:06.820 --> 00:22:09.319
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Well,
I've done a little bit of that.

00:22:09.319 --> 00:22:12.620
You know, this WPP Group,
which I bought years ago--

00:22:12.620 --> 00:22:14.370
I sold some in 2000.

00:22:14.370 --> 00:22:16.870
It was selling at a crazy price,
and didn't get it all sold,

00:22:16.870 --> 00:22:18.280
but I kept it.

00:22:18.280 --> 00:22:21.694
And then you know I knew
Martin Sorrell and watched him.

00:22:21.694 --> 00:22:23.110
But then I watched
other companies

00:22:23.110 --> 00:22:26.840
come along, like this one.

00:22:26.840 --> 00:22:30.400
And you know, it was hurting
their business very badly.

00:22:30.400 --> 00:22:33.040
So I eventually sold it.

00:22:33.040 --> 00:22:36.864
And I made good sales, too.

00:22:36.864 --> 00:22:38.280
That would be a
reason-- you know,

00:22:38.280 --> 00:22:40.040
if the business is
fundamentally changed

00:22:40.040 --> 00:22:46.079
by technology or by something
that they haven't done.

00:22:46.079 --> 00:22:48.620
That would be the reason to sell
it, or the management's bad,

00:22:48.620 --> 00:22:51.810
or something had changed
that you could see.

00:22:51.810 --> 00:22:55.580
But not because it didn't show
relative strength or something

00:22:55.580 --> 00:22:57.070
crazy like that.

00:22:57.070 --> 00:22:59.720
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: Shad, if we
can shift gears a little bit,

00:22:59.720 --> 00:23:02.120
you've spoken about the
need for pension funds

00:23:02.120 --> 00:23:05.180
to be simple in their
investing process.

00:23:05.180 --> 00:23:06.890
And recently, there
have been incidents

00:23:06.890 --> 00:23:11.134
of funds that have invested
in exotic foreign agriculture

00:23:11.134 --> 00:23:13.850
and things that
didn't work out well.

00:23:13.850 --> 00:23:17.300
Why do you think this
happens, and what

00:23:17.300 --> 00:23:19.847
can be done to improve this?

00:23:19.847 --> 00:23:22.430
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: If you'll
think of yourself as a stock,

00:23:22.430 --> 00:23:23.000
I think it helps.

00:23:23.000 --> 00:23:25.310
You know, you have more money
coming in than going out,

00:23:25.310 --> 00:23:28.220
hopefully, and you all are
in there to buy stocks,

00:23:28.220 --> 00:23:30.169
and your estate grows.

00:23:30.169 --> 00:23:32.460
And you get a better job or
you don't get a better job,

00:23:32.460 --> 00:23:35.480
but you're spending
less than you're saving,

00:23:35.480 --> 00:23:39.266
then you're grow up and you're
going to be rich old guy

00:23:39.266 --> 00:23:41.600
or girl or whatever.

00:23:41.600 --> 00:23:43.395
And that's the way it works.

00:23:43.395 --> 00:23:45.020
And these pension
funds have more money

00:23:45.020 --> 00:23:46.920
going out than coming in.

00:23:46.920 --> 00:23:50.190
And compound interest is the
eighth wonder of the world,

00:23:50.190 --> 00:23:52.966
but when it's working against
you, you can't beat it.

00:23:52.966 --> 00:23:54.965
That's what's happening
in these pension funds--

00:23:54.965 --> 00:23:57.480
they promise more
than they can deliver.

00:23:57.480 --> 00:24:01.080
And so they're saying
they're making money--

00:24:01.080 --> 00:24:03.780
or they're only 75% funded,
or something like that.

00:24:03.780 --> 00:24:06.410
But really, they're
going to go broke.

00:24:06.410 --> 00:24:10.400
And you can be an
alarmist about it.

00:24:10.400 --> 00:24:11.150
I got fired--

00:24:11.150 --> 00:24:12.983
I was the Chairman of
the Texas Review Board

00:24:12.983 --> 00:24:15.140
for 12 years or something.

00:24:15.140 --> 00:24:19.870
And you know, Governor
Perry finally fired me.

00:24:19.870 --> 00:24:22.670
He got tired of listening,
tired of hearing me.

00:24:22.670 --> 00:24:25.522
But compound interest
is a wonderful thing

00:24:25.522 --> 00:24:27.230
to have on your side
and a terrible thing

00:24:27.230 --> 00:24:29.205
to have working against you.

00:24:29.205 --> 00:24:30.830
PRANESH SRINIVASAN:
Do you think that's

00:24:30.830 --> 00:24:32.977
likely to change in the
coming years, the way--

00:24:32.977 --> 00:24:34.560
FREDERICK "SHAD"
ROWE: Oh, sure, it'll

00:24:34.560 --> 00:24:38.657
change-- like, the sun will
come up in the west or the east

00:24:38.657 --> 00:24:39.490
or wherever it does.

00:24:39.490 --> 00:24:41.150
You know, no.

00:24:41.150 --> 00:24:44.056
They're immutable laws.

00:24:44.056 --> 00:24:45.540
It isn't going to change.

00:24:45.540 --> 00:24:47.924
Behavior isn't going to change.

00:24:47.924 --> 00:24:49.590
People get hold of
other people's money.

00:24:49.590 --> 00:24:50.131
They like it.

00:24:50.131 --> 00:24:53.914
It gives them power, and
they want to be smart.

00:24:53.914 --> 00:24:55.830
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: So
Shad, one of the books,

00:24:55.830 --> 00:24:57.380
I think, that have
really influenced

00:24:57.380 --> 00:24:59.994
you has been "Money
Masters," by John Train.

00:24:59.994 --> 00:25:01.160
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Yeah.

00:25:01.160 --> 00:25:03.950
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: What
about the book influenced you?

00:25:03.950 --> 00:25:06.241
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Well,
he's a good money manager.

00:25:06.241 --> 00:25:09.140
And he understood
the distinctions

00:25:09.140 --> 00:25:11.140
that investors were
making in their minds.

00:25:11.140 --> 00:25:12.140
It's just a good survey.

00:25:12.140 --> 00:25:13.595
And nothing's
changed since then.

00:25:13.595 --> 00:25:15.720
No one had ever studied
investment managers before.

00:25:15.720 --> 00:25:17.780
They were just kind of
like clerks, or something.

00:25:17.780 --> 00:25:22.040
Then they became kind of
larger than life, sometimes,

00:25:22.040 --> 00:25:25.030
and it became
interesting to people.

00:25:25.030 --> 00:25:27.335
But the thing I
found interesting--

00:25:27.335 --> 00:25:30.870
he's very thoughtful,
and one time I said,

00:25:30.870 --> 00:25:32.870
after studying
all these people--

00:25:32.870 --> 00:25:35.210
value investors
and all this-- how

00:25:35.210 --> 00:25:37.400
did you become a
growth stock manager,

00:25:37.400 --> 00:25:39.180
at, like, T. Rowe Price?

00:25:39.180 --> 00:25:42.700
And he said that value
investors are really

00:25:42.700 --> 00:25:43.950
kind of glorified accountants.

00:25:43.950 --> 00:25:47.360
They're looking at the gap
between their perceived value

00:25:47.360 --> 00:25:49.474
and what the assets
are going to be worth

00:25:49.474 --> 00:25:51.140
and its market
capitalization and trying

00:25:51.140 --> 00:25:52.795
to close the difference.

00:25:52.795 --> 00:25:54.170
And then when they
do it, they've

00:25:54.170 --> 00:25:55.550
got to go buy something else.

00:25:55.550 --> 00:25:57.050
So it's a constant
turnover process.

00:25:57.050 --> 00:25:59.240
If you ever make a mistake,
you pay a lot of taxes,

00:25:59.240 --> 00:26:01.180
and you've lost all your money.

00:26:01.180 --> 00:26:03.690
But a growth stock
investor, which, he said--

00:26:03.690 --> 00:26:04.980
that suited his nature--

00:26:04.980 --> 00:26:07.322
you're really kind
of a futurologist--

00:26:07.322 --> 00:26:09.530
looking in the future and
trying to figure out what's

00:26:09.530 --> 00:26:10.400
going to happen.

00:26:10.400 --> 00:26:13.760
He said that suited his
nature, so that's what he did.

00:26:13.760 --> 00:26:15.796
That makes perfect sense to me.

00:26:15.796 --> 00:26:18.120
And it requires fewer
people, and you just

00:26:18.120 --> 00:26:20.790
have to be right a couple
of times in your life.

00:26:20.790 --> 00:26:22.831
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: When
we were speaking earlier

00:26:22.831 --> 00:26:25.940
with one of your
colleagues, [INAUDIBLE],,

00:26:25.940 --> 00:26:28.160
you spoke about the
spectrum of investors--

00:26:28.160 --> 00:26:30.830
short sellers, activists,
long only investors.

00:26:30.830 --> 00:26:32.350
Do you want to
share that with us?

00:26:32.350 --> 00:26:32.810
FREDERICK "SHAD"
ROWE: I was just

00:26:32.810 --> 00:26:35.960
saying that short sellers really
think that they're the smartest

00:26:35.960 --> 00:26:37.970
people on Earth,
that they're much

00:26:37.970 --> 00:26:39.960
smarter than these managements.

00:26:39.960 --> 00:26:44.030
And they're so smart, they'll
risk their whole stash

00:26:44.030 --> 00:26:46.120
to prove they're right.

00:26:46.120 --> 00:26:48.539
And they either go broke
or have nervous breakdowns

00:26:48.539 --> 00:26:49.580
or just shoot themselves.

00:26:49.580 --> 00:26:52.160
I mean, I know a guy who
tried to just killed himself.

00:26:52.160 --> 00:26:54.990
But it's a terrible life.

00:26:54.990 --> 00:26:58.860
And then the next ones are the
activist investors-- activists.

00:26:58.860 --> 00:27:00.860
They think they're smarter
than management, too.

00:27:00.860 --> 00:27:03.070
They're going to tell
them how to do it.

00:27:03.070 --> 00:27:05.620
So they just get in
there and start saying,

00:27:05.620 --> 00:27:07.440
do this, do this, do that.

00:27:07.440 --> 00:27:10.880
And we want to sell the company
and want to make these fees.

00:27:10.880 --> 00:27:11.870
And then--

00:27:11.870 --> 00:27:12.700
PRANESH SRINIVASAN:
The value investors.

00:27:12.700 --> 00:27:15.033
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: And
then the value investors I've

00:27:15.033 --> 00:27:16.064
already talked about.

00:27:16.064 --> 00:27:16.980
You can rank them all.

00:27:16.980 --> 00:27:19.064
And then the growth stock
investors just think--

00:27:19.064 --> 00:27:20.480
this company is
smarter than I am,

00:27:20.480 --> 00:27:21.650
they know the business
better than I do,

00:27:21.650 --> 00:27:23.060
plus it's a great business.

00:27:23.060 --> 00:27:24.976
And it if isn't,
I'll get out of it.

00:27:24.976 --> 00:27:27.395
That's how you have a
slight advantage, there.

00:27:27.395 --> 00:27:29.520
You want to put yourself
on the side where you have

00:27:29.520 --> 00:27:31.720
an advantage, and they don't.

00:27:31.720 --> 00:27:34.170
So if you perceive that
there's a long term

00:27:34.170 --> 00:27:35.347
future for the business--

00:27:35.347 --> 00:27:37.180
they're doing simply
better, faster, cheaper

00:27:37.180 --> 00:27:41.300
and for the customer, you can
buy it at a reasonable price,

00:27:41.300 --> 00:27:43.560
and if you're wrong,
you can sell it--

00:27:43.560 --> 00:27:45.690
that's a pretty good deal.

00:27:45.690 --> 00:27:49.360
And that's one I
think I want to take.

00:27:49.360 --> 00:27:53.550
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: So Shad, I
want to get a little personal

00:27:53.550 --> 00:27:54.810
with this question for you.

00:27:54.810 --> 00:27:57.850
So around two decades ago,
you were diagnosed with

00:27:57.850 --> 00:27:58.580
Parkinson's.

00:27:58.580 --> 00:27:58.790
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Yeah.

00:27:58.790 --> 00:27:59.700
PRANESH SRINIVASAN:
Shortly afterwards you

00:27:59.700 --> 00:28:01.300
considered shutting
down your fund.

00:28:01.300 --> 00:28:02.502
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE: Yeah.

00:28:02.502 --> 00:28:04.960
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: But then
you chose not to shut it down.

00:28:04.960 --> 00:28:07.332
Maybe you should
walk us through that.

00:28:07.332 --> 00:28:08.790
And also, after
that, you've stated

00:28:08.790 --> 00:28:10.830
that having Parkinson's
has actually

00:28:10.830 --> 00:28:14.220
made you a better person.

00:28:14.220 --> 00:28:16.590
Can you talk to us--
why you feel that?

00:28:16.590 --> 00:28:17.490
FREDERICK "SHAD" ROWE:
Well, Michael J. Fox,

00:28:17.490 --> 00:28:18.210
I'm on his board.

00:28:18.210 --> 00:28:21.760
He calls up-- Parkinson's is
a gift that keeps on taking.

00:28:21.760 --> 00:28:24.390
But I think it makes you
a little humble and more

00:28:24.390 --> 00:28:26.325
appreciative of what you
did have going right.

00:28:26.325 --> 00:28:28.120
You have to make
adjustments to it.

00:28:28.120 --> 00:28:32.554
But my first reaction was what
the hell is going on here?

00:28:32.554 --> 00:28:34.470
And I thought, well,
I'll do everybody a favor

00:28:34.470 --> 00:28:36.270
and shut the fund down.

00:28:36.270 --> 00:28:37.620
And I gave all the money back.

00:28:37.620 --> 00:28:39.060
I had some stocks that
were hard to get out

00:28:39.060 --> 00:28:40.183
of-- they were illiquid.

00:28:40.183 --> 00:28:42.590
And so I dragged my
feet and then decided--

00:28:42.590 --> 00:28:44.447
what else am I going to do?

00:28:44.447 --> 00:28:46.905
So I changed my mind and have
had a good record ever since.

00:28:46.905 --> 00:28:48.363
I had a good record
the whole time,

00:28:48.363 --> 00:28:55.200
but yeah, it changes
your life a little bit.

00:28:55.200 --> 00:28:59.250
And you appreciate the
things that go your way,

00:28:59.250 --> 00:29:01.020
and the things that
don't, you don't

00:29:01.020 --> 00:29:03.780
worry as much about,
which is meaning to say--

00:29:03.780 --> 00:29:07.170
I'm kind of a completely
pleasant personality-- is not.

00:29:11.210 --> 00:29:13.740
But you know, I think investing
is a matter of finding out

00:29:13.740 --> 00:29:16.380
who you are and where
you fit in the world

00:29:16.380 --> 00:29:18.140
and how it all fits together.

00:29:18.140 --> 00:29:19.170
You know, I don't know
whose saying it is,

00:29:19.170 --> 00:29:20.670
but-- if you don't
know who you are,

00:29:20.670 --> 00:29:23.680
the stock market is an
expensive place to find out--

00:29:23.680 --> 00:29:24.635
is true.

00:29:24.635 --> 00:29:28.420
But if you fit your nature
with your investment style,

00:29:28.420 --> 00:29:32.540
and it makes economic sense,
you can probably do pretty well.

00:29:32.540 --> 00:29:34.534
If you think of
yourself as a stock--

00:29:34.534 --> 00:29:36.450
where you have more
coming in than going out--

00:29:36.450 --> 00:29:38.366
and so you're doing
something with the money--

00:29:38.366 --> 00:29:40.770
in other words, you're
managing your cash flow--

00:29:40.770 --> 00:29:43.430
you're going to end up
being a rich old guy or girl

00:29:43.430 --> 00:29:44.720
or whatever.

00:29:44.720 --> 00:29:47.410
And that makes sense to me.

00:29:47.410 --> 00:29:51.010
So I feel like the
game is going my way.

00:29:51.010 --> 00:29:52.800
And I feel like that's
the way anybody who

00:29:52.800 --> 00:29:54.270
thought about it should go.

00:29:54.270 --> 00:29:55.930
And if you listen
to the television--

00:29:55.930 --> 00:29:57.390
the stocks are
under accumulation,

00:29:57.390 --> 00:30:00.840
it's breaking out, it's breaking
down, it's lacking support--

00:30:00.840 --> 00:30:03.890
I'm selling, I'm selling,
buy-sell, buy-sell.

00:30:03.890 --> 00:30:07.050
Just pay a lot of commissions
and dealer spreads

00:30:07.050 --> 00:30:12.480
and lose your money
and talk more.

00:30:12.480 --> 00:30:14.700
PRANESH SRINIVASAN: So
Shad, before we open it up

00:30:14.700 --> 00:30:16.710
to the audience for
questions, I want

00:30:16.710 --> 00:30:19.590
to ask you one question
that we ask all our guests.

00:30:19.590 --> 00:30:22.650
What is some advice you would
give the personal investor,

00:30:22.650 --> 00:30:26.540
someone who's starting their
journey today, maybe investing

00:30:26.540 --> 00:30:30.420
their first few dollars and
trying to make compounding

